‚Äú11 years old. That was the first time I ever got politically engaged. I ran for junior block captain. We were living on this block, which is in the district I now represent. And I remember telling my mom whatever my 11 year-old brain could muster. Like, there's this issue in the block, that issue. I'm coming home and telling my mom these things. And she's like, well, if you care so much, go do something about it. And I was like, oh, okay. Lol. So I ran for junior block captain. And that really sparked in me a broader commitment to civic engagement. And then in college, I got engaged in a lot of stuff around LGBTQ rights and women's rights and climate justice and all these different things. And when it became clear that my predecessor may not run for office, I quit my job and was like, I'm running for office. 
This place we‚Äôre right now in is equal parts exciting, but also so deeply and viscerally frustrating. What we're talking about is the floor, not the ceiling. And certainly not the sky.¬†¬†The reason we're dealing with this is because America has never addressed its structures, which are so deeply broken, right? This is not about a one-off thing. The structure itself is inherently broken. And we're finally at a point where all those things that we've talked about -- finally, during a hot summer in Philly, we're going to make sense of where we‚Äôve never been. This idea that you can actually have life, liberty, and pursuit of your happiness. This idea that we all actually are created equally. So it means something to me that Joe Biden was always one of the poorest members of Congress. We want to address issues around poverty. And it's particularly potent in this moment that he's one of few legislators to never own a stock when we have a government that's deeply corrupt. And run by folks who are super well off and well connected. He brings this very real lived experience of somebody who knows what it means to not have everything handed to you. And to have to work incredibly hard. He understands what my mom understood: that we all have a responsibility irrespective of where we come from to get involved, to get engaged. To be a part of the solution.‚Äù

caption:
‚ÄúI was born in Philly to a teenage mother and a father who was serving a life sentence. He was actually released just in time to attend my college graduation, which was last year. So when it came to my mom, one big thing for her was always education. You know, there were such limited opportunities here for Black people. It was like, okay, ‚ÄòYou're going to do well in school. We're going to do these activities.‚Äô I did everything from horseback riding classes to playing ice hockey and the violin. And that's how my mom helped me to succeed, go to college and beyond. So, one thing that we always talked about was Black history and Black figures and how they have, you know, fought for us and resisted for us to exist today and how we're now able to have basic freedoms. 
I think I was a sophomore at Spelman or I was a rising sophomore and I was struggling to afford to go back. And that summer, another Black man was murdered at the hands of police. I had little money to go back to school even though I had filled out scholarships. Spelman, you know, it‚Äôs an HBCU, so there's limited funding. But I created these shirts and we sold them in my community in West Philadelphia to support my education and involve my community members. ‚ÄúI'm a Black man‚Äù came from Dr. King. What it says is: I am a man, no matter the color, I'm a man. And then in his letter from the Birmingham jail that he wrote, he talked about how, if he were in Germany, when it was illegal to help Jews and be on their side, he would have done it anyway because they are people and he understood their plight. So when I wear the shirt, it's me saying, I'm a Black man. Mind you, I am a Black, cis woman. But I align with the struggle of all Black people. So I'm no different than any other Black person, I'm no different than any other human. So this shirt says, I'm in solidarity. I understand you. I see you. I see us.

caption:
Fifty years ago, the first Earth Day took place against a backdrop of unfettered pollution filling our skies, rivers so poisonous they caught fire, unregulated use of pesticides, and threats to the livability of our planet. But in a moment of choice, Americans all across this country took action. On April 22, 1970, 20 million people turned out to educate their communities and protest the degradation of our planet, launching the modern environmental movement.

It wasn‚Äôt a partisan issue. It wasn‚Äôt some ideological debate. Everyone could see that our planet was in peril. And by acting together, those activists seized the attention and the imagination of people all over the world, as well as leaders in Washington. Out of that first Earth Day came the Environmental Protection Agency, the Clean Air Act of 1970, the Clean Water Act, the Endangered Species Act, and a new mindset that awakened all of us to our responsibilities beyond just the world we leave our children ‚Äî to ensuring that our one planet will provide for generations unborn.

This year, Earth Day comes amid global crises: the difficult, immediate, and undeniable reality of pandemic disease, and the existential threat of climate change ‚Äî which we are already experiencing and which threatens equally deadly results in the near future if we fail to act. COVID-19 and the climate emergency both underscore the fragility of life on this planet, the connections that bind us to our fellow humans, and the responsibility we all have to meet these global threats with urgent action, ambitious plans, and every tool at our disposal.

That‚Äôs the responsibility I feel every time I look at my grandchildren and see their unlimited potential. Or when I hear from young activists who understand that inaction today is costing their futures. Today‚Äôs young people carry the same fierce spirit as those first Earth Day activists, and they are the reason I know we will succeed in spurring the world to finally raise our ambitions to meet the seriousness of this threat.

Read more: [Link in Bio]

On #EarthDay, we're reminded that there is no more urgent crisis facing this nation, or the world, than the threat posed by climate change. We have to take drastic action before it‚Äôs too late ‚Äî and that‚Äôs exactly what I will do as president.

Health care is personal to me. I was sworn into the United States Senate next to a hospital bed. My wife and daughter had been killed in a car crash ‚Äî and lying in that bed were my two surviving little boys. I couldn‚Äôt imagine what it would have been like if we didn‚Äôt have the health care we needed immediately.

Forty years later, one of those little boys, my son Beau, was diagnosed with terminal cancer and given only months to live. Through the hardship, I saw firsthand how important it is to have quality, affordable coverage ‚Äî it means peace of mind that your medical bills won‚Äôt drown you in debt and helps provide hope that things will get better.

This fight is personal to me ‚Äî like it is for so many Americans. And I promise you that if I‚Äôm elected president, I will protect your family‚Äôs health care coverage as if it were my own.

accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Joe Biden on March 23, 2019 tagging @barackobama, @dccl, and @speakerpelosi. Image may contain: 5 people, people standing and suit.
caption:
Nine years ago today, the Affordable Care Act was passed into law. You may remember that I had a few words to share with President Obama about how important I thought this bill was... Almost a decade later I still feel just as strongly. Not only did we increase the number of Americans with health insurance by 20 million by the time we left office, but we expanded the rights of all Americans by banning insurers from denying coverage or increasing premiums due to pre-existing conditions, requiring insurers to cover recommended preventive services including certain cancer screenings, and eliminating annual lifetime caps on insurance coverage.

This law has made a difference in the lives of countless Americans who now have the peace of mind that health care offers. 
That is a BFD.

accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Joe Biden on December 01, 2018 tagging @dccl. Image may contain: 1 person, sitting, table and indoor.
caption: On behalf of the whole Biden family, Jill and I would like to offer our deepest condolences, thoughts, and prayers to George, Jeb, Neil, Marvin, Doro, their children, and the entire Bush family. They have lost a father and grandfather. And this nation has lost a great leader. When we went to Houston in 2015 to honor the doctors that cared for our deceased son Beau, President Bush insisted on coming out to see us. He wanted to personally welcome us to Houston and offer his condolences for the loss of our son. That was George H.W. Bush‚Äîdecent, kind, and welcoming. With President Bush it was seldom about himself. Always about others. His life of service was legendary. From the moment he signed up as an 18-year-old Naval aviator a few months after Pearl Harbor and for every step after that in his lengthy career as a diplomat, Congressman, Vice President, and President‚ÄîGeorge H.W. Bush chose a path of service. He was a man who presided over the peaceful end to the Cold War and the reunification of Germany. This was statesmanship and leadership of historic dimensions. So much could have gone wrong but instead went right because of his leadership. This is how history will rightly remember him. Every American‚Äîand arguably everybody on Earth‚Äîowes him a debt of gratitude for being such an able steward. Over the course of the many years we worked together‚Äîand against each other‚Äîon the biggest issues of the day, differences of policy were always based on substance. It was never personal. It was never petty.  It was always with respect for our institutions and the people they govern. As we mourn his passing today, we remember a life totally and completely dedicated to the country he loved.

accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Joe Biden on November 19, 2018 tagging @dccl. Image may contain: one or more people and crowd.
caption: Last fall my book #PromiseMeDad was published and I crisscrossed the country to meet with readers. What has been most surprising and most gratifying is the number of people who come to the book events not for politics, but for need of comfort. For connection. That simple act of offering solace to other people has been the most rewarding service I have performed in my time out of public office. It seems to be much needed these days. And the truth is, feeling like I can provide some small measure of balm for people in pain has helped me heal. I‚Äôll be visiting a few more cities on the #AmericanPromiseTour before the end of the year, and hope to see you if I‚Äôm coming to your town. More information is available at joebidenbook.com.

accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Joe Biden on November 05, 2018 tagging @dccl. Image may contain: 8 people.
caption: I have traveled to 22 states. Campaigned for 63 candidates. And in the last six days alone, hit 13 different towns. Everywhere I go, there‚Äôs an insatiable desire for women and men of character in high public office. Because folks, this year, the very character of our country is on the ballot: Fairness, decency, respect, equality. Giving every one of God‚Äôs children a fair shot. Tomorrow, we have the opportunity to stand up for real American ideas. To make it clear that Democrats choose hope over fear. Unity over division. Truth over lies. But you have to show up and vote. Bring five of your friends with you. It‚Äôs time to get up and remember who we are. This is America. And together, we can take it back.

accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Joe Biden on October 25, 2018 tagging @andrewgillum, and @nelsonforsenate. Image may contain: 2 people.
caption: There‚Äôs something different about this year‚Äôs elections. You can just feel it in your gut. It‚Äôs something bigger than politics. Something that gets to the very core of who we are. Folks, America is an idea -- based on a set of values. Decency. Respect. Giving hate no safe harbor. Leaving no one behind. It‚Äôs about a commitment to something bigger than ourselves. This is America. And together, we can take it back. But we've got to remember who we are. And we can‚Äôt leave a single vote on the table. Vote early, vote by mail, vote on Election Day on November 6. However you do it -- just be sure you do one thing. Vote.

accessibility_caption: Photo by Joe Biden in Survivor Tree, 9/11 Memorial.
caption:
It‚Äôs a basic American instinct to respond whenever help is needed and to comfort the afflicted. It‚Äôs an American instinct summoned by our collective strength. An instinct that echoes through the ages ‚Äî from Pearl Harbor, to Beirut; from Mogadishu to Ground Zero; from Flight 93 to the Pentagon. And in the wake of those dark moments, our spirit became mightier. The bonds that unite us became thicker. 
Seventeen years after the 9/11 attacks, may we continue to live that legacy -- in our words and our deeds, every day. In America, we can overcome anything.

We've become so divided in our political discourse online that we hardly hear each other anymore.  We shout and attack and pay less and less attention each day to what matters.

What do I mean by ‚Äúwhat matters‚Äù? Well, for starters: this fall, millions of Americans will head to the voting booth, where they'll elect people with the ability to make real and concrete changes in all of our lives. 
It will be one of the most consequential elections of any of our lifetimes. We will be voting to remind the world who we are, and the people we elect will be charged with upholding our values and preserving our shared character -- the things that make us Americans. 
Before this election, I want us to have a real discussion about what really matters -- the fundamental issues that determine whether or not all of us are given a chance to live with dignity and to pursue opportunity. 
I've partnered with the folks over at @attndotcom to talk through some these issues, and I'm excited to start sharing our work with you in the days to come. I want to hear your feedback, your opinions and your thoughts.  And I want you to take that energy with you to the polls in November. Stay tuned.

accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Joe Biden on September 06, 2018 tagging @supportthewalk. Image may contain: 5 people.
caption:
Over the course of the past three months, a team of wounded veterans from the United States and the United Kingdom have been walking across the country together -- from coast to coast. They are raising awareness for the tens of thousands of warriors who return home from battle with post-traumatic stress or traumatic brain injuries. We owe them. Today, Jill and I finished the walk with them in New York City. Their courage knows no bounds, and their bond and service transcends national borders. 
I'm proud to know them, and grateful to have the chance to once again share my days with you here on @instagram. It's good to be back.
